<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06333012 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06333012 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Hatch  </CAPTION><LEADPARA>  Sen. Orrin Hatch's dealings with a businessman linked to the BCCI bankingscandal and a Texas developer are being investigated by law-enforcementofficials, sources close to the investigation said Wednesday. The UtahRepublican was involved in business deals with Houston entrepreneur MunzerHourani, and met several times with Mohammed Hammoud, a Lebanese businessmanconnected with the bank, the sources said.;   The Bank of Credit and CommerceInternational is at the center of a worldwide scandal involving alleged drugmoney laundering, arms trafficking and support of terrorists. BCCI, founded byPakistanis as a Third World bank, had $20 billion in assets and operated insome 70 countries -- including the United States -- before it was shut down inJuly by regulators in several nations. Hammoud, a BCCI shareholder, operatedas a key front for the outlaw bank, the sources said on condition they not beidentified. NBC News quoted Hourani as saying that Hatch once offered to helphim get money from BCCI.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HATCH'S DEALINGS WITH 2 IN BCCI CASE INVESTIGATED  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Washington News in Brief  </MEMO><TEXT>     Hatch acknowledged that he did make a phone call in 1990 &quot;to facilitate theintroduction&quot; of Hourani to BCCI. Hatch also released copies of a letter froma Justice Department official telling Hatch that he is neither a subject or atarget of BCCI investigations by the department. Hatch said he had nofinancial interest in BCCI.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911128  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  18A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STA